    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter" xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Frans van Cranevelt to Miklós Oláh (Mechelen, 4 October
                    1537)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">1. He has read <hi rend="italic">Hungaria</hi>, which
                            filled him with awe, and if there had been enough time, he would have
                            copied it. But he does not want to delay him now because of the moving,
                            he only asks him to publish it, this work should not be hidden. 2. He
                            has heard that a book was published in Paris in which they accuse the
                            Emperor. He is also attaching his letter to Theodor Adam Svallenberg in
                            case someone from Oláh is going to Paris and can hand it over to him. He
                            also sent Oláh’s epitaph the day before yesterday, along with his (von
                            Cranevelt’s) Latin translation, if he does not like one, he should use
                            the other.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.1"><del corresp="Olahus">Francis</del><add corresp="Olahus"
                        type="insert">Franciscus</add> Cranneveldius Nicolao Olao salutem. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.2">[1.] Perlegi, quanta potui celeritate, <hi rend="italic"
                        >Hungariam</hi> tuam, Vir Ornatissime, in qua et naturae benignitatem et
                    vivacissimum ingenium tuum sum magnopere demiratus, quo tot insignium locorum
                    dotes, tot fluvium <del corresp="Olahus">dotes</del> cursus, tot hominum
                    praeclara facinora complecti tam exacte, tanta sermonis luce potuisti. Si per
                    temporis brevitatem licuisset, continuo exscripturus eram. Nunc, <del
                        corresp="Olahus">quod</del> cum adornari peregrinationem hanc novam
                    intelligam, non fuit consilium tuum <hi rend="italic">Athilam</hi> diutius
                    invitum retinere, ne mihi quoque negotium facessat, illud autem abs te cupio
                    impetrare, ne vir tantas inter chartas tuas diutius delitescat, sed in publicum
                        prodeat,<note xml:id="note.1"><hi rend="italic">Athila</hi> was only
                        published in 1568, by János Zsámboky. On the editions of Oláh’s historical
                        works, see <hi rend="smallcap">Tóth</hi> 2019, 124.</note> mirifica
                    voluptate studiosos omnes affecturus. Quid enim possit esse praeclarius
                    historiarum exacta cognitione? Sed vereor, ne nostro quoque tempore propter <del
                        corresp="editor">propter</del> hominum scelera rursus exoriatur divinum
                    aliquod flagellum ad mores hominum castigandos luxumque domandum. Omne in
                    praecipiti vitium stetit, et quantum est in rebus inane? Utinam Deus precibus
                    bonorum piorumque virorum flectatur ad misericordiam, quamquam ea quoque magna
                    misericordia est, quam <del corresp="Olahus">pates</del><add corresp="Olahus"
                        type="corr">pater</add> exhibet <milestone unit="pb"/>filio improbo, dum
                    castigat et flagrum adhibet, cum sanari aliter non vult lenioraque remedia
                    contemnit. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.3">[2.] Audivi ex <persName>Brugensi</persName><note xml:id="note.2">We
                        do not know him more closely.</note> quodam, qui
                        <placeName>Parrisiis</placeName> fuit et latuit hoc bello, Gallos edidisse
                    libellum recenti fetura XXXVI plus minus <del corresp="Olahus"
                        >quateniores</del><add corresp="Olahus" type="corr">quaterniones</add>
                    continentem, in quo multa adversus caesaream maiestatem calumniantur.<note
                        xml:id="note.3">For more, see <hi rend="smallcap">Detering–Pulia</hi>
                        2020.</note> Mirum est principes vulgi iudicio causam committere, et quaedam
                    aperire mysteria, quae postea <del corresp="Olahus">forsitam</del><add
                        corresp="Olahus" type="corr">forsitan</add> occultata cuperent. Sic bellum
                    gerere deberent, veluti memores aliquando sese in gratiam redire posse. <quote
                        xml:id="quote.1">Sic oderis, inquit ille, tamquam aliquando
                        amaturus.</quote><note type="quote" xml:id="note.quote.1">Erasm. <hi
                            rend="italic">Adag</hi>. 1072. II, I, 72. Ama tanquam osurus, oderis
                        tanquam amaturus.</note> Mitto his adiunctas litteras ad
                        <persName>Zwallembergum</persName>,<note xml:id="note.4">Theodor Adam
                        Svallenberg.</note> qui <placeName>Parisiis</placeName><del corresp="Olahus"
                        >et</del><add corresp="Olahus" type="corr">est</add> in collegio
                    Cameracensi, quas licebit aperire et si quis <del corresp="Olahus"
                        >istius</del><add corresp="Olahus" type="corr">istinc</add> eo proficiscitur
                    mittere, nam hinc nemo proficiscitur. Misi nudiustertius litteras unacum
                    epitaphiis tuis et Graeco illo pro virili mea in Latinum converso duplici
                        versione,<note xml:id="note.5">See Ep. 592. and the text editions of the
                        poems: <hi rend="smallcap">Ipolyi</hi> 595. Cranevelt translated Oláh’s
                        Greek poem. For the original poem see <hi rend="smallcap">Neagu</hi> 2003,
                            350.<ref>olahus.tei.15371004_1</ref></note> ut si altera minus arrideat,
                    utaris altera, nisi malis utramque <quote xml:id="quote.2">in spongiam
                        incumbere</quote>.<note type="quote" xml:id="note.quote.2">Suet. <hi
                            rend="italic">De vitis caesarum,</hi> Div. Aug. 85: “respondit, Aiacem
                        suum in spongeam incubuisse”.</note><note xml:id="note.6">Cranevelt liked
                        citing this line, see Ep. 585.<ref>olahus.tei.15370428_1</ref></note> Vale,
                    Vir Ornatissime, et Craneveldium inter tuos <choice>
                        <orig>munera</orig>
                        <supplied>numera</supplied>
                    </choice>. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.4"><placeName>Mechliniae</placeName> 4. <choice>
                        <orig>Ionas</orig>
                        <supplied>Nonas</supplied>
                    </choice> Octobris 1537.</p>
            </div>
